sections.Dioritic Inclusions:
Dioritic Inclusions
The interiors of zircon from the dioritic samples 27c and 42a yield 238 U-230 Th age populations of 28 6 5 and 24 6 5 ka, which are indistinguishable from the zircon interiors and rims from the late Pleistocene rhyolite (Figure
6b
). Several dioritic zircons have interiors that are as old as 260 ka (Figure
7
). Dioritic sample 304a has younger zircon cores (8 6 5 ka). Rims on zircon from dioritic sample 27c mostly yield model ages that are younger than their interiors, with an apparent age population at 11.5 6 1.2 ka (F 5 0.67). However, a subset of zircon rims with 238 U/ 232 Th activity ratios <8 define a horizontal (zero-age) isochron (Figure
10
), suggesting a somewhat higher initial 232 Th/ 230 Th for these rims than indicated by the whole-rock composition and crystallization within millennia of the 2006 eruption. A significant fraction of rims yield model ages defining a population at 29 6 3 ka, which is indistinguishable from the rhyolite-hosted zircon. Two diorite zircon in secular equilibrium for ( 230 Th)/( 238 U) yielded U-Pb ages of 90 Ma and 1800 Ma (Table
4
). Geochemistry, Geophysics, Geosystems 10.1002/2014GC005589 U concentrations of dioritic zircon are more variable than those from rhyolite and range from near zero to 700 ppm, including a distinct cluster of 25 ka grains that range from 400 to 700 ppm U (Figures
6b
and
8
). These high-U zircon have low Hf (<0.85 wt %) and high Ti (20-50 ppm). They also have elevated REE abundances relative to all other analyzed Augustine zircon (Figure
9
).
Ti concentrations for high-U zircon are consistent with apparent temperatures of 850 to greater than 950 C, using the range of aTiO 2 of 0.67-0.77 calculated using touching Fe-Ti oxide pairs from diorite samples (Figure
8
). It is possible that Fe-Ti oxides record aTiO 2 that is lower than that of the melt the zircon originally crystallized in, and aTiO 2 is best reflected by rhyolite Fe-Ti oxides, which yield aTiO 2 of 0.85. In this case Ti-in-zircon records temperatures of 830-940 C. Regardless of uncertainties in absolute temperature recorded by Ti-in-zircon [e.g.,
Reid et al., 2011]
, it is clear that the high-U zircon record higher temperatures than low-U grains.

sections.2006 Andesites:
2006 Andesites
Rare, small zircons were recovered from highsilica andesites (62.5 wt % SiO 2 ) erupted in 2006. Unpolished zircon rims yield a population with a mean age of 9 6 6 ka (Figure
6c
), with a handful of zircon ages that are older, but notably few to none in the age range of 25 ka observed for zircon of the rhyolite and diorite. Most andesite-hosted zircon have U (20-200 ppm), Hf (0.64-0.95 wt %), and Ti (8-15 ppm) concentrations that generally overlap with the low-U diorite zircon (Figure
8
), though  Geochemistry, Geophysics, Geosystems 10.1002/2014GC005589  Geochemistry, Geophysics, Geosystems 10.1002/2014GC005589 two grains have higher U (Figure
7
). Two rims (304c-2.1 and 3.1) have 1700 ppm U (not shown), are in 230 Th-238 U secular equilibrium, and are likely true xenocrysts.
